        <div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-pre-header-section">=
<div class=3D"section-container"><p>A <strong>Maclaurin series</strong> is =
a <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/power-series/" class=3D"wiki_link" =
title=3D"power series" target=3D"_blank"><strong>power series</strong></a> =
that allows one to calculate an approximation of a function <span><span cla=
ss=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/=
1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><=
mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applic=
ation/x-tex">f(x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=3D"kate=
x-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" sty=
le=3D"height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class=3D"mord mat=
hnormal" style=3D"margin-right: 0.1076em;">f</span><span class=3D"mopen">(<=
/span><span class=3D"mord mathnormal">x</span><span class=3D"mclose">)</spa=
n></span></span></span></span> for input values close to zero, given that o=
ne knows the values of the successive derivatives of the function at zero. =
In many practical applications, it is equivalent to the function it represe=
nts.  </p>

<p>An example where the Maclaurin series is useful is the sine function.  T=
he definition of the sine function does not allow for an easy method of com=
puting output values for the function at arbitrary input values.  On the ot=
her hand, it is easy to calculate the values of <span><span class=3D"katex"=
><span class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Ma=
thML"><semantics><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo>=E2=81=A1</mo><mo stretchy=3D"false"=
